<TEXT>
<P>
Authorities in Newark, N. J., agreed to scale back drastically the amount of 
public housing to be demolished under a slum clearance plan and committed 
themselves to replacing the razed apartments. The agreement between the Newark 
Housing Authority and housing activists provides for the demolition of eight 
apartment buildings containing about 1,900 units, with 1,500 new apartments to 
be built and hundreds of others renovated. Tenants in buildings being 
demolished will be given a place immediately in a new building or a renovated 
apartment. The program is the biggest demolition of public housing by an 
American city. It is aimed at getting rid of what critics call "high-rise 
slums." 
